    <body><div type="letter">
      <p>Brighton 4th Augst. 8 o'clock</p>
      <p>My Dearest. Today has been hot &amp; very fine. I drove the Hen's phaeton this morning at 1/2 pst 11 to Rottingdean to fetch Mrs King, &amp; have just been taking her a part of the way back in an open fly. I have also been in the chair this afternoon, so the Bird has been well aired.-- I call on Aunt Lucy &amp; saw her today. She is a</p>
      <p>nice goodnatured old lady, &amp; expresses a wish to see you again. I also called on Emily, who was out. She &amp; I have not yet met. Perhaps she does not much wish it. I know nothing of her proceedings. Mrs. Gooch did just mention her the other day, &amp; being Mrs Spier's mother &amp; much at Brighton, could probably tell me much about her, were I to seek it.</p>
      <p>Hester &amp; I had some curious conversation today, on religious subjects. She has a most excellent understanding, &amp; I could</p>
      <p>not have had a sister more to my taste.--</p>
      <p>I was mistaken in what I hinted to you yesterday about myself, but suppose I am hardly likely to escape during the next week.--</p>
      <p>I think of returning to Ockham on Monday or Tuesday week, when I believe the Hen leaves.-- She desires her love.--</p>
      <p>I wish I could express to ou what pleasure ou dear letters give me.--</p>
      <p>Ou Birdie A K</p>
    </div></body>
